Comminuted and displaced pathologic fracture of the distal femur through the distal shaft extending to the growth plate. Abnormal lucent lesion in the distal shaft with heterogeneous sclerosis in the metaphysis. Smooth layered periosteal reaction and sclerosis in the proximal femur shaft. Soft tissue swelling along the dorsal aspect of the distal femur. No large knee joint effusion. The differential diagnosis would include chronic osteomyelitis, Brodies abscess and pathologic fracture and pathologic fracture on the basis of aggressive bone lesions including Ewing sarcoma, osteosarcoma, LCH and lymphoma. It needs to be correlated with clinical and if available with surgical findings.

Left femur, 2 views
Indication: Osteomyelitis, pyomyositis.
Comparison: None.
Findings: The patient is imaged in a splint, which obscures fine bone detail. There is a fracture of the distal femoral diaphysis with mild apex anterior and lateral angulation. There is lamellated periosteal reaction extending along the proximal femur to the level of the lesser trochanter. This is greater than expected for periosteal reaction related to healing fracture, and is compatible with the given history of osteomyelitis. Evaluation is limited by the splint, but there is no definite bony destruction. Limited evaluation of the soft tissues.
Impression:
1. Mildly angulated distal left femoral fracture.
2. Lamellated periosteal reaction extending along the proximal femur, greater than expected for healing fracture. This is compatible with osteomyelitis. No definite bony destruction within limitation due to overlying splint. Recommend follow up xrays, with splint removed if possible.
